**Totals:** 7 occurrences across 2 files (4 in OrderProcessor, 3 in NotificationService).

---

## Recommendation: Use `TimeProvider` (.NET 8+)

.NET 8 introduced `System.TimeProvider` — an abstract class designed exactly for this:

```csharp
public class OrderProcessor
{
    private readonly TimeProvider _time;

    public OrderProcessor(TimeProvider? time = null)
        => _time = time ?? TimeProvider.System;

    public Order CreateOrder(...)
    {
        var now = _time.GetUtcNow();
        // use 'now' instead of DateTime.UtcNow
    }
}
```

**In tests**, use `Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing.FakeTimeProvider`:

```csharp
var fake = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var processor = new OrderProcessor(fake);

// Advance time deterministically
fake.Advance(TimeSpan.FromDays(31));
Assert.True(processor.IsExpired(order));
```

**If targeting < .NET 8**, define a simple interface:

```csharp
public interface IClock
{
    DateTimeOffset UtcNow { get; }
}
```

Inject it the same way. Both approaches eliminate the static coupling and make all time-dependent logic fully deterministic in tests.

